<TEXT>
two men were charged late thursday with 
murder in connection with the slaying of a wesleyan university 
student activist who police said had joined with them in a drug 
distribution ring 
carl lightner 20 and kumar viswanathan 21 were charged with 
murder and conspiracy to commit murder in connection with the death 
of nicholas b haddad who was found fatally shot in a car carrying 
a cache of semiautomatic weapons 
lightner has been in custody since he was arrested july 7 on an 
unrelated drug charge he was to be arrested and arraigned on the 
murder charges friday bond on those charges was set at 550000 
viswanathan was still at large late thursday police said but a 
hartford superior court judge set his bond at 750000 authorities 
said they believe viswanathan has fled hartford 
police said haddad and the two suspects had set up a drug 
distribution center in hartford haddad supplied the cash and the 
other men bought and sold the drugs police said 
haddad was to receive a share of profits from sales made by the 
other two the two suspects reportedly lost or misspent a large sum 
of haddads money and fearing reprisal plotted to kill him 
police said 
haddad was lured to keney park in hartford on july 6 and shot to 
death police said 
his participation in protests against the treatment of 
minorities at wesleyan and his recent purchases of semiautomatic 
weapons had led authorities to wonder if the slaying was connected 
to two firebombings at wesleyan in april but authorities no longer 
think that is the case 
hartford states attorney john m bailey said police found 
absolutely no connection between the murder and activities on 
the wesleyan campus bailey also said there was no sign that the 
slaying was racially motivated 
haddad 21 a lebaneseamerican who had spent about 17 years in 
lebanon identified with the black community at wesleyan during 
the spring black students complained that police had unfairly 
singled out haddad and several other minority group members as 
suspects in the firebombings 
police denied having any suspects although a hartford courant 
reporter visiting the middletown police station reported seeing 
memorandums posted identifying three students as principal suspects 
family members said they were just as puzzled as police over 
what happened 
in a eulogy at a funeral mass on wednesday haddads cousin 
also named nicholas haddad said his slain cousin had wanted to 
embrace the person he had become not the person we wanted him to 
be 
we all worried about him in the end said the cousin he did 
not elaborate 
when haddads body was found police said they recovered an 
undisclosed number of semiautomatic weapons from the car including 
an israelimade uzi he bought for 1000 
all were legally purchased last month from a gun shop three 
miles from the campus of wesleyan an elite private university with 
an enrollment of 2700 
police said his interest in firearms had become an obsession 
in the past month 
reggie cann a wesleyan graduate student said he and haddad 
were both members of a support group for black students 
he considered himself african cann said 
he liked to live a mysterious life and it was hard to tell 
when he was telling the truth said one former wesleyan student 
who spoke on condition of anonymity 
haddad who listed red hook ny as his home address was 
coeditor of a new student publication called the afrikan nation 
and had helped organize several rallies this spring protesting the 
treatment of minorities at wesleyan and around the world 
the cover of the publications first edition said in creative 
struggle the embrace of love and war will give birth to the new 
afrikan nation 
haddad and nine other students went on a nineday hunger strike 
in may following the discovery of racist graffiti in the basement 
of a black student dormitory 
the activists said the graffiti was the product of a climate of 
racial intolerance at wesleyan 
haddad had been notified in june that because of academic 
deficiencies he would have to take at least two semesters off 
before being considered for readmission the university said he 
had however remained in the area after the end of the school year 
university officials had only last semester named haddad a 
mellon fellow a fellowship intended to encourage top minority 
students to pursue careers as professors 
</TEXT>
