<TEXT>
the associated press and its technical employees 
have agreed to submit three areas of dispute in their contract 
talks wages pensions and health benefits to nonbinding 
arbitration 
a representative of the ap and a representative of the 
communications workers of america were to discuss those issues in a 
nonbinding arbitration process starting today it was announced 
wednesday 
that process was to last 48 hours under the terms of the expired 
contract between the union and the news service at the end of that 
period the two sides could select an outside arbitrator if there 
were unresolved issues 
on july 3 the cwa said a proposed twoyear contract had been 
voted down overwhelmingly no vote totals were announced 
the 300 technical employees affected have been working under 
contract extensions since early june 
the ap has urged the adoption of a managed care approach to 
control the cost of the medical plan and offered weekly pay 
increases of 2350 for topscale technical employees in the first 
year and 24 in the second year bringing weekly topscale salaries 
to 612 in 1991 
the union wants a larger raise and wants the company to pay a 
larger portion of health care costs 
the union also has proposed pension increases which the company 
has declined to offer 
</TEXT>
