<TEXT>
only the swans that beg for bread on 
the banks of the neisse river seem oblivious to the fact that 
guben like berlin is a city divided by war 
for more than 700 years guben east germany and gubin poland 
were the same city but aside from a bridge that spans the neisse 
lttle else links these towns 
like germany and its old capital guben was carved in half by 
world war ii few people however are calling for the 
reunification of guben 
we wont see a united guben said juergen kunze vice mayor 
of the east german city i hardly see any contacts on a 
voluntary individual basis 
both cities today are drab gray relics of the former communist 
regimes that ruled poland and east germany until democratic 
revolutions spread through the east bloc last year 
each city stands now less as a symbol of the past than as a 
reflection of the different paths east germany and poland are 
pursuing 
both nations are experiencing high prices labor unrest and 
joblessness as the cost of dismantling their socialist systems and 
moving to the free market 
but east germany is being aided by west germany and its chances 
for achieving prosperity are expected to be far better than 
polands 
east germany merged its economy with west germanys on july 1 
and the powerful west german mark became the currency of the former 
communist country 
now better food and and higher quality household goods fill the 
stores on the east german side 
ruth hulke 55 was born on the eastern side of the river and 
was moved to the west after the war 
before east germanys borders were opened last fall she said it 
was easier for poles than east germans to travel to west germany 
poles would buy coveted goods in the west then resell them to east 
germans 
until recently she said she used to travel to the polish side 
to buy products that were not available in east germany 
now we dont need to go there any more she said 
marek dutkiwicz 25 a television repairman from the polish 
side said goods are cheaper now in east germany than in poland 
about 34000 people live in guben and 17500 poles live in the 
city across the river about 1500 poles work in the german town 
but few germans work on the other side of the river 
the original guben was chartered in the 13th century and has 
been part of prussia saxony and germany 
after germanys defeat in world war ii the allies extended the 
polish border into german lands to make up for polish territory 
ceded to the soviet union the border of the newly created east 
germany was drawn at the oder and neisse rivers 
guben which straddled the neisse was cut in two 
what was the central part of guben became part of poland and was 
renamed gubin the smaller western section of town was left for 
east germany 
most of the prewar buildings were destroyed during the war so 
there are few landmarks from the days when guben was a single 
german city 
many of the former residents fled to what is now west germany to 
escape the approaching soviet army poles from the lands seized by 
the soviets were resettled in gubin so there are few residents who 
remember the prewar days 
barbara remus an editor at the guben newspaper the lausitzer 
rundschau said there has been friction between citizens of the two 
cities 
before east germany merged its economy with west germanys 
poles would buy up statesubsidized inexpensive goods in the east 
german town and sell them in west germany at a profit 
but when the polish border was opened in february she said many 
germans from guben streamed to the polish side to buy goods 
many poles fear that a united germany will seek to reclaim its 
former lands which comprise about onethird of presentday poland 
but miss remus said there are no such stirrings in the german 
side of guben 
it used to all be one guben but its accepted that gubin is 
polish she said nobody says they want it back 
</TEXT>
