<TEXT>
thousands of customers of a private 
savings bank in warsaw have something to worry about the banks 
owner has apparently disappeared 
lech grobelny the founder of the bko savings bank and owner of 
a chain of currency exchanges has not returned from a holiday 
abroad the prosolidarity newspaper gazeta wyborcza reported 
wednesday 
bko which in polish stands for safe savings bank was founded 
at the end of last year and offered interest rates of up to 180 
percent much higher than rates at the stateoperated banks 
last year polands inflation rate was 244 percent but it has 
dropped sharply this year as the solidarityled governments 
economic shock therapy program took effect 
as it moves toward a marketbased economy the new government 
has deregulated the banking industry allowing private banks to be 
formed and compete with stateowned banks 
but regulatory safeguards are apparently not yet in place 
according to the report grobelny left poland on june 6 for a 
twoweek holiday in an undisclosed location employees told the 
newspaper they last heard from him in late june when he informed 
them he would return home july 6 
rumors of the bko owners disappearance have been circulating 
for several weeks in warsaw and the banks cash reserves have 
shrunk due to increased withdrawals 
about 10000 customers have accounts with bko with deposits 
worth some 32 billion zlotys or 33 million dollars according to 
the daily 
bko did not meet standards set by the national bank of poland 
for private banks and the government had several times warned the 
public that their deposits with it might not be safe 
on monday employees informed the prosecutors office about 
grobelnys absence explaining that no substitute had been 
appointed before his departure to take care of the company 
warsaw provincial prosecutor jacek kryszczuk interviewed by the 
pap news agency said he saw no grounds for legal action until an 
official complaint by a customer is filed 
the bko office was closed on wednesday and a group of customers 
who wanted to take their savings back could only read a note on the 
door saying that they can vindicate their claims at a district 
court pap said 
</TEXT>
