<TEXT>
president violeta barrios de chamorro 
announced late wednesday that she would negotiate with militant 
prosandinista leaders of a general strike that has threatened to 
topple her 10weekold government 
at the same news conference gen humberto ortega head of the 
army and a member of the leftist sandinistas nineman directorate 
until march said the army would quiet the capital within hours 
i feel very sure i will serve out my term said mrs 
chamorro expressing confidence her government has survived its 
most serious challenge since defeating the sandinistas at the polls 
in february 
a wave of strikes began july 2 and turned violent when 
protesters opposing the strikes took to the streets on friday tens 
of thousands of government workers have closed down public 
services strike leaders say 90000 workers have walked out since 
the strike began 
the unions that called the strikes the army and police are all 
loyal to the sandinistas who ruled the country for nine years and 
are now the main opposition to mrs chamorros usbacked 
administration 
mrs chamorros confidence she will serve until 1995 stemmed 
from the promise of the sandinista peoples army to obey her 
command to restore order 
ortega said the army would never back a coup at the same time 
he made it clear the military would stop short of allout force 
against the strikers 
the armed forces he said will never carry out a coup against 
any government here much less the government of dona violeta but 
neither will the army and police fire on the people 
at the news conference which was attended by the us and 
soviet ambassadors and other members of the diplomatic corps mrs 
chamorro reversed her earlier insistence that the strike must end 
before talks could begin 
she said she was willing to negotiate once the streets were 
cleared of barricades basic public services were restored and 
strikers cleared from government installations 
ortega claimed the army would have managua back to nearnormal 
thursday 
he said four people had been killed and 15 to 20 wounded in 
confrontations between sandinista strikers and government 
supporters the nicaraguan human rights commission earlier 
estimated 84 injured 
police and army loyalty have been a key issue since mrs 
chamorro defeated ortegas brother daniel ortega in the feb 25 
elections 
earlier wednesday an explosion knocked a progovernment radio 
station off the air and its director blamed the sandinistas 
presidential spokesman danilo lacayo said mrs chamorro called 
for public condemnation of the bombing he said the president had 
ordered a police investigation 
radio corps transmitter and antenna were blown up after 
leftist sandinista organizers told strikers to ease their grip on 
managua and demanded mrs chamorro who took office april 25 open 
negotiations immediately 
the station had been converted into a stronghold for armed 
opponents of the strikes the protesters abandoned their takeover 
at the station at tuesday midnight saying they reached an 
agreement with police 
daniel ortega had charged the station was calling on the 
government to request us military intervention to end the strikes 
no one claimed responsibility for the explosion but radio 
station director castillo osejo said in an interview he blamed 
the sandinistas because nobody else would be interested in doing 
such a thing 
the strikers are demanding more participation in economic 
planning and dispute proposals to cut back civil service workers 
hired by the sandinistas the civil servants won 100 percent pay 
raises in a may strike 
mrs chamorros coalition the 14party united national 
opposition offered the layoffs as part of a plan to restart the 
nicaraguan economy which was ruined during the 9year civil war 
with the usbacked contra rebels and a trade embargo imposed 
during the reagan administration 
meanwhile air traffic controllers went back to work wednesday 
and said the airport was open although no flights were arriving or 
departing 
a few barricades came down in the capital and gunfire ended in 
the morning but strikers still occupied most government ministries 
and some staterun industries 
the government has declared the strikes illegal it suspended 
talks over the weekend 
a statement issued by the sandinistarun national workers 
front which controls most of the striking unions urged strikers 
to create conditions favoring the start of talks allowing the 
circulation of people and transport in areas where the sandinista 
police demand it 
the statement read on prosandinista radio ya proposed that 
negotiations begin wednesday afternoon 
the day before mrs chamorro issued a statement that central 
american presidents asked that violence end to create a climate 
of calm to permit a negotiated solution 
the developments wednesday did not seem to make a major 
difference in daily life in managua although a few more people 
were in the streets 
witnesses said soldiers helped build barricades despite orders 
that they restore peace in the capital 
managua continued without public transportation most grocery 
stores remained closed barricades and trenches dug across streets 
stopped most traffic 
bomb blasts and gunfire were heard overnight but no reports of 
casualties surfaced 
state radio nicaragua claimed wednesday that a minority of 
some 3000 armed sandinistas control the city and are keeping more 
than 1 million people hostage 
