<TEXT>
when it comes to gobbling up energy there is 
no equal to uncle sam 
witnesses told two house subcommittees wednesday that since 1985 
programs by some federal agencies to conserve energy have virtually 
disappeared especially at the defense department which accounts 
for 80 percent of the governments energy requirements 
according to energy department estimates the federal government 
spent 35 billion last year to heat light and cool more than 
500000 buildings while spending only 445 million to make 
buildings more energyefficient the governments total energy bill 
came to more than 8 billion including fuels for the military 
after dramatic gains in energy efficiency in the late 1970s and 
early 80s energy use has once again been on the increase at 
federal facilities according to the government figures cited at 
the congressional hearing federal agencies used about 1 percent 
more energy per square foot of building space last year than five 
years ago between 1975 and 1985 the government cut energy use by 
17 percent 
two years ago energy conservation efforts by the government 
slowed to a crawl and continue to lag despite a law that 
requires the government to cut energy costs by 10 percent by 1995 
said rep philip sharp dind chairman of the house energy and 
power subcommittee 
comparatively few federal installations have participated in 
energy saving programs even where such programs were substantially 
financed by someone else said rep mike synar dokla who is 
chairman of the government operations subcommittee on environment 
energy and natural resources 
in recent years energy conservation has taken on renewed 
interest because of environmental concern over emissions from the 
burning of fossil fuels environmentalists have argued that the 
nation must dramatically reduce its energy use if it is to deal 
with global warming and other environmental problems 
government figures show that the defense department which spent 
more than 1 billion on energy conservation during 197585 
allocated only 15 million last year to make buildings more 
energyefficient 
jeffrey jones director of energy policy at the defense 
department said the pentagon plans soon to establish new programs 
aimed at improving energy efficiency he expressed confidence the 
10 percent energy reduction goal by 1995 can be met 
the federal government has a large stake in energy 
conservation yet the us government lags far behind the private 
sector in purchasing and installing energy conservation systems 
douglas decker manager of government markets for johnson controls 
inc told the hearing 
johnson controls inc of milwaukee wis is a major 
manufacturer of energy management systems for commercial buildings 
decker cited government figures that showed that while some federal 
agencies have reduced energy consumption per square foot others 
have increased their demand significantly 
among the agencies that have cut energy use substantially since 
1985 were the commerce department 23 percent justice department 
21 percent environmental protection agency 19 percent and 
transportation department 14 percent 
but energy use at the federal energy regulatory commission 
jumped nearly 18 percent while it rose by 11 percent at the 
general services administration and nearly 29 percent at the office 
of personnel management at the defense department by far the 
governments largest user energy use per square foot increased 14 
percent during the four years 
meanwhile a report by the general accounting office the 
investigative arm of congress cited a variety of problems in 
cutting government use of energy including budgetary concerns 
with serious deficit problems budget planners are reluctant to 
allocate money for energy efficiency improvements although the 
payback may be only a few years said gao investigator nye stevens 
but the energy savings are not possible without spending 
that additional money up front he added 
the gao also said the government lacks central direction and 
responsibility for energy conservation and that federal procurement 
practices inhibit the use of various energy conservation programs 
used by industry 
 
</TEXT>
