<TEXT>
marvin liebman a father of the modern 
conservative movement is helping smash gay stereotypes by publicly 
declaring his homosexuality according to gay political leaders 
i think its important not only to have a founder of the 
modern conservative movement speak out against bigotry its 
important for american society as a whole for someone with a 
distinguished career to say i am a gay american and i am not 
ashamed said gregory king communications director for the 
human rights campaign fund a gay political lobby 
urvashi vaid executive director of the national gay amp lesbian 
task force another lobbying group said liebmans statement is a 
welcome one 
for years weve said theres an enormous diversity in the gay 
and lesbian movement vaid said wednesday there are gay 
progressives and gay conservatives 
liebman revealed his homosexuality this month in the pages of 
william f buckleys conservative national review and the advocate 
a los angelesbased gay magazine 
in an interview wednesday liebman 66 said he decided to 
announce hes gay because he sees signs that the political right is 
becoming dangerously bigoted 
the primary impact i wanted to have in this whole coming out 
was on the conservative community just to sort of alert them to 
the dangers of homophobia and all that comes with it he said 
but roger stone a conservative political consultant said he 
did not think liebmans statement would affect the conservative 
movement 
i think it will be viewed as the actions of an individual 
stone said adding that he did not believe bigotry was growing 
among conservatives 
liebman first made his revelation in a letter to buckley whom 
he describes as his best friend 
i am both gay and conservative and i dont find that a 
contradiction liebman wrote in the july 9 issue of the national 
review 
explaining why he chose to go public now liebman continued i 
fear that our cause might sink back into the ooze in which so much 
of it rested in prenational review days in that dark age the 
american right was heavily perhaps dominantly made up of bigots 
buckley who once suggested that gay people with aids be 
tattooed on the buttocks and called gore vidal a queer on 
national television responded by asking if its reasonable to 
expect the larger community to cease to think of the activity of 
homosexuals as unnatural whatever its etiology 
however buckley also wrote that he understood liebmans 
pain and promised the national review will not be scarred by 
thoughtless gaybashing 
liebman said wednesday he feels no rancor toward buckley even 
though they disagree on whether homosexuality is moral or normal 
there is nothing that bill buckley could say that would offend 
me or make me feel bad liebman said this is just the way the 
man thinks 
born in brooklyn ny liebman was a jew until age 55 when he 
converted to roman catholicism buckley was his godfather 
at 15 liebman had joined the young communist league and for 
years was active in other communist front groups he served two 
years in the army air corps but was discharged in 1944 for being 
homosexual a fact he kept secret until this month 
after the war liebman joined irgun an underground zionist 
organization and worked as an organizer and fundraiser until the 
early 1950s liebman worked for a variety of leftleaning groups 
but his politics shifted and he teamed with buckley and others 
to pioneer the modern conservative movement he founded the young 
americans for freedom and was active in the conservative party of 
new york and the presidential campaigns of barry goldwater and 
ronald reagan 
liebman came to washington after reagan was elected in 1980 
working first as a consultant to the federal government from 1982 
to 1987 he was director of public affairs and special projects at 
the national endowment for the arts he is now director of special 
projects at the federal trade commission 
