<TEXT>
an international conference to discuss the future 
of vietnamese boat people has been postponed in a continued 
disagreement over repatriation of nonrefugees 
raymond hall spokesman for the office of the united nations 
high commissioner for refugees said wednesday that no new date has 
been set for the conference which had been scheduled for july 
1617 
hall called the delay very dangerous and said risks were 
growing that countries near vietnam would refuse to allow boat 
people to land on their shores he said about 112000 boat people 
are in southeast asian refugee camps 
he said the delay could threaten the un principle of first 
asylum under which refugeseekers are granted temporary asylum 
until they are resettled in other nations or repatriated to their 
homeland 
a un meeting last year agreed on an international plan to cope 
with the flood of vietnamese boat people including the 
introduction of screening procedures to separate genuine refugees 
those escaping political persecution from migrants in search of a 
better life 
it also set up a program to repatriate people wishing to go back 
to vietnam so far 3400 have returned voluntarily hall said 
however disagreement continues over the fate of nonrefugees 
who are unwilling to be sent back 
the bush administration remains opposed to the forcible 
repatriation of economic migrants diplomats in geneva say us 
officials privately are showing some flexibility 
hanoi also is reluctant to accept involuntary returns 
britain under pressure from its overcrowded hong kong colony 
and southeast asian nations have demanded the united states agree 
to mandatory repatriation or set up its own camps to accommodate 
nonrefugees 
at a meeting in manila in may southeast asian countries issued 
an ultimatum that they would stop granting asylum if no settlement 
was reached 
hall said the high commissioner had agreed to postpone next 
weeks meeting because of lack of common ground among participants 
the united states and other resettlement countries firstasylum 
countries and vietnam 
he said intense negotiations were taking place but a further 
meeting was unlikely to take place before august 
hall said by the end of may there were 112000 boat people in 
camps in the region up from 83000 in may 1989 about 55000 are 
in in hong kong 
