<TEXT>
richard b bernstein a professor of 
chemistry at ucla whose work in molecular chemistry earned him a 
national medical of science award has died he was 66 
bernstein died in helsinki finland on sunday after suffering a 
heart attack he was attending a conference of soviet and american 
scientists 
bernstein joined the faculty of the university of california 
los angeles in 1983 and pioneered research of interactions between 
molecules 
his work in molecular beam scattering earned him the national 
medal of science in 1989 and he received the prestigious robert a 
welch award in chemistry in 1988 
with ahmed h zewail of the california institute of technology 
bernstein developed femto chemistry which employs lasers to 
observe the birth of molecules almost as they happen 
a member of the national academy of sciences bernstein 
initiated the academys first study of the impact of 
chlorofluorocarbons or cfcs on the earths ozone layer 
prior to joining ucla bernstein was chairman of the chemistry 
department at columbia university in new york 
as an undergraduate at columbia he became a member of the 
manhattan project the united states secret effort to develop the 
atomic bomb during world war ii he received his doctorate at 
columbia in 1948 
bernstein also taught at the university of texas the university 
of wisconsin and the university of michigan and served as a senior 
vice president of occidental research corp in irvine 
bernstein is survived by his wife norma a son three 
daughters a brother and four grandchildren 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

