ferdinand 
justice sandra day oconnor who handles emergency appeals to 
the high court from california denied the request wednesday her 
action upheld a ruling tuesday by the 9th us circuit court of 
appeals in san francisco 
the appellate court ruled in favor of the los angeles times 
which sought access to papers concerning hamilton in us district 
court in los angeles the 21 appellate ruling says 
the risk that harm or injury will befall mr hamilton as a 
result of the release of these documents is no greater than the 
risk that all public figures are subject to daily by virtue of the 
fact that their activities may become the subject of favorable or 
unfavorable mention in the news media 
that is a risk that mr hamilton as a sometime motion picture 
and television actor as well as a noted man about town is in any 
event subject to at all times 
the ruling was written by judges dorothy w nelson and stephen 
reinhardt said federal deputy clerk ernie cruz in san francisco 
hamilton was out of the country and unavailable for comment 
said a secretary for his publicist jeffrey lane who also was out 
of his office 
a message left with hamiltons attorney after hours was not 
returned 
