<TEXT>
texas officials said today that oileating 
microbes dumped on part of an oil slick from the wrecked 
supertanker mega borg appeared successful in eating the oil while 
not harming the environment 
if you believe your eyes it was a great success texas land 
commissioner garry mauro said at a news conference today test 
results from the small application show no evidence that the 
microbes produced any toxic byproducts and no evidence of change 
in the nutrient balance of the natural marine environment 
best of all the tests show that the microbes ate the oil 
mauro said adding that the surface oil in some samples was 
reduced to 30 percent of the original volume 
the process called bioremediation involves the use of 
microorganisms that are dumped on oil 
the naturally occurring bacteria reduce the oil to an emulsion 
of fatty acids this emulsion sinks and is consumed by marine life 
while the microbes die after the oil is gone 
the microbes were dropped on part of the slick from the mega 
borg which was left crippled in the gulf of mexico after an 
explosion june 8 an estimated 39 million gallons of angolan crude 
leaked from the vessel although much of that was consumed by fire 
the bioremediation tests on the spill cost the state 26000 
mauro and bj buck wynne chairman of the texas water 
commission said they were pleased with the results and were ready 
to push forward to have bioremediation included in companies oil 
spill contingency plans 
