<TEXT>
mouth cancer kills nearly 10000 people a year in 
the united states and unlike other cancers survival rates arent 
getting better federal health officials said thursday 
the atlantabased centers for disease control said oral and 
pharynx cancers killed 9742 americans in 1987 the latest year for 
which statistics are available that works out to 36 deaths per 
100000 people the same rate it was back in 1973 said cdc dental 
health specialist linda crossett 
and the survival rate hasnt changed in 16 years the cdc said 
only 52 percent of oral cancer patients survive five years or more 
thats in contrast to the survival rates for breast colorectal and 
prostate cancer which are improving 
federal health officials have set a national goal of cutting 
oral cancer deaths in middleage americans by 15 percent to 30 
percent by the year 2000 
were not making a lot of progress crossett said looking 
at new cases now about 30000 americans are diagnosed with oral 
cancers each year 
the survival rates are lower for blacks and getting worse 
just 31 percent of black patients survived oral cancer in 198186 
statistics compared with 35 percent in 197476 
for whites the survival rates have remained more constant 53 
percent in 198186 55 percent in 197476 
major risk factors for oral cancer include tobacco use either 
smoked or smokeless and drinking and the combined risks from 
tobacco and alcohol use appear to be substantially greater than 
those from tobacco or alcohol alone the cdc said in its weekly 
report 
the increased use of tobacco among women adolescents and 
children as compared to a decline in smoking overall is 
likely to elevate death rates for these cancers in the next several 
decades the report said 
in addition to continued use of tobacco the other major reason 
for oral cancer deaths is the fact that there has not been any 
improvement in early detection crossett said most are only 
detected after theyve grown pretty large so advanced that 
its obvious 
traditionally a dentist has been most likely to perform a 
thorough oral exam on a patient but the cdc noted a 1986 survey 
showing that people at highest risk for oral cancer sought the 
services of a standard physician four times more often than they 
went to the dentist 
and many people going to their physician may not get a 
thorough oral head and neck exam crossett said thats the 
big key early detection 
