a bill that would divide the states 13 electoral votes by 
congressional districts was up for a state senate vote today after 
passage by the house last year but the vote was delayed until 
friday or next week because a cost analysis hadnt been completed 
said sen tom taft chairman of the senate election laws committee 
the democratcontrolled state legislature is expected to redraw 
congressional district lines in 1992 republicans fear the new 
system would leave democrats with control of all 13 electoral votes 
currently whichever candidate garners a majority in a state 
wins all the states electoral votes 
maine adopted the alternative method in 1969 but it has made no 
difference in the way the states electoral vote has been 
allocated a similar proposal passed the connecticut house this 
session but died in the senate after the governor hinted he would 
veto it 
in north carolina where republican gov jim martin has no veto 
power the senate was on its way to approving the bill wednesday 
when republican lt gov jim gardner ruled the measure must be 
accompanied by a fiscal note showing how much its passage might 
cost the state 
republicans acknowledged the move was a delay tactic 
under the bill candidates would receive one electoral vote for 
each of the 11 congressional districts they win north carolinas 
two remaining electoral votes would go to the candidate who carried 
the state 
