the house appropriations committee on thursday 
approved a 170 billion spending bill for federal health labor and 
education programs next year 4 billion more than president bush 
requested 
the appropriations bill continues provisions from past years 
prohibiting spending federal medicaid money for abortions for poor 
women except in cases where the life of the mother is in danger 
abortionrights supporters succeeded in adding language to a 
similar bill last year that expanded that exception to include 
medicaid abortions for victims of rape and incest but bush vetoed 
the bill because of the broadened abortion provisions and the 
house failed to override his veto 
because of parliamentary roadblocks abortion rights lawmakers 
said they probably would not attempt to add abortion provisions 
when the spending bill goes to the house floor probably next 
thursday 
however they said they expected the senate to add a similar 
amendment when it debates the spending bill triggering a repeat of 
the 1989 fights when the bill returns to the house for concurrence 
the bill provides 76 billion for the department of labor in 
fiscal 1991 it authorizes 1357 billion for the department of 
health and human services 26 billion for the department of 
education and 1 billion for related agencies 
the total represents a 173 billion increase over 1990 spending 
and a 42 billion increase over the amount requested by bush in 
his proposed 1991 budget 
rep william natcher dky chairman of the appropriations 
subcommittee that wrote the bill said it included money set aside 
for major child care and aids prevention bills that are nearing 
passage 
nearly threequarters of the bills money goes to mandatory 
entitlement programs such as medicare medicaid welfare and other 
programs in which spending is required by previously passed law 
it includes 439 billion in discretionary programs an increase 
of 56 billion over comparable amounts in 1990 spending and 32 
billion more than requested by bush 
