<TEXT>
a violent sandinista strike that 
threatened to topple president violeta barrios de chamorro ended 
early thursday with her government agreeing to more major 
concessions as a price of survival 
the strike accord dilutes mrs chamorros power to trim a 
bloated public payroll and to reverse what her economic advisers 
see as a crippling legacy of more than a decade of leftist 
sandinista rule 
public employees won an immediate 43 percent raise with another 
unspecified raise to come next month 
it was the second major wage concession for nicaraguas 65000 
government employees who got a 100 percent raise after a may 
walkout in addition to government workers thousands of employees 
of staterun industries also stayed off the job inthe latest strike 
in addition the government agreed not to carry out its threat 
to fire those taking part in what it had declared an illegal 
walkout and to pay compensation to 800 people fired since mrs 
chamorros april 25 inauguration 
the strikers also forced the conservative government to back 
down on a key part of its plan to return nicaragua to a freemarket 
economy the return of lands confiscated in the 1979 revolution 
but the price of survival was high and the support the army and 
police gave mrs chamorro appeared limited both were party organs 
under the sandinistas 
mrs chamorro said late wednesday she wouldnt negotiate until 
the strikers met certain conditions but secret talks began within 
hours and the accord with the sandinistaled national workers front 
was announced early thursday 
the president had said a dialogue could begin only after the 
streets were clear of the barricades that had paralyzed the capital 
since sunday strikers vacated occupied government installations 
and basic public services were restored 
although the violence that claimed at least six lives had ended 
the capital was still a maze of paving stone barricades or their 
debris when talks began and many buildings were still in the hands 
of strikers 
managua began returning to normal thursday although its pocked 
and scarred streets were still a motorists nightmare taxis were 
circulating businesses were reopening and the union had told 
strikers to go back to work the only concession the strikers made 
both sides were declaring victory in a confrontation the united 
states and president chamorro had called an attempt to destablize 
her government 
despite her concessions mrs chamorro portrayed her government 
as a winner it had not fallen and she and her advisers called the 
armys decision not to back the strikers a triumph 
army and police bulldozers had removed barricades but most 
blockades were rebuilt without interference and there were no 
arrests 
in addition to putting the brakes on returning confiscated land 
to prerevolutionary owners the agreement opens the door to 
