<DOCNO> AP900712-0119 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
us consumers are paying as much as 1 
billion too much annually for international telephone calls the 
federal communications commission said thursday in proposing to 
make it easier for us carriers to negotiate lower rates with 
overseas phone companies 
the commission said us phone companies in 1988 paid 2 billion 
more to foreign usually governmentoperated phone companies 
than they collected from foreign carriers for international calls 
about half that amount represented an overpayment by us 
consumers to foreign carriers the fcc said 
intense competition among us phone companies since the 1984 
breakup of the bell system has pushed prices down for international 
calls but has resulted in foreign companies gaining a larger share 
of the charges for such calls fcc chairman alfred sikes said 
before the commissions 50 vote 
competition and technological progress in telecommunications 
has revealed a cartellike pricing and profitsharing 
arrangement sikes said us subscribers and those in a 
handful of other countries are both the winners and losers 
companies such as atampt negotiate accounting rates that 
determine how atampt and a foreign company will divide the charges 
consumers pay for international calls under present formulas 
about 75 cents of every dollar collected by us carriers for 
international calls goes to foreign carriers 
atampt contends foreign governments are charging far above the 
actual cost of service and that because more calls flow from the 
united states to other countries than in the reverse direction 
having accounting rates that exceed costs results in a significant 
outflow of us dollars to other nations 
some overseas phone carriers use the funds to finance local 
service and say it is vital to their economies 
atampt argues that what foreign entities will lose in lower 
accounting rates they will more than make up in the increased 
volume of calling resulting from lower prices 
the fcc proposed to allow us companies to negotiate lower 
accounting rates more quickly the commission also proposed to 
lower the accounting rates itself if it finds that costs are too 
high 
atampt welcomed the commissions proposal 
company spokesman herb linnen said the proposal sets up the 
possibility of lowering accounting rates for all of the us 
carriers and that can translate into savings for consumers 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

