<TEXT>
oileating microbes dumped on a slick from a 
leaking tanker in the gulf of mexico apparently did their job 
gobbling up oil without hurting the environment officials said 
thursday 
state land commissioner garry mauro and texas water commission 
chairman bj buck wynne said that while more testing is 
needed there is enough evidence to push for expanded use of the 
process called bioremediation 
we have strong evidence that bioremediation works mauro 
told a news conference the results show that we are close to 
having a tool that actually cleans up oil spills 
the microbes were tested after the norwegian tanker mega borg 
exploded june 8 and burned 57 miles off galveston an estimated 39 
million gallons of light crude leaked into the gulf 
much of the oil burned but some created a slick that appeared 
headed toward the texas coast 
skimmers and booms were deployed but mauro and wynne pushed to 
test the microbes the test done first on about 40 acres of the 
spill and again on a smaller patch was not a major part of the 
cleanup 
mauro and wynne said thursday there is no evidence the microbes 
caused any environmental damage 
both said the microbes should be used again on the next 
significant oil spill and should be tested on smaller spills near 
the texas coast 
the test on the mega borg spill marked the first time the 
microbes were used in open waters bioremediation had been used 
before to clean up hazardous waste sites extract oil from tight 
geologic formations and clean some rocks on shore after the exxon 
valdez spill in alaska last year 
the naturally occurring bacteria reduce the oil to an emulsion 
of fatty acids which sinks and is eaten by fish when the oil is 
gone the microbes die 
we found surface oil was reduced after the application and we 
found no similar reduction in the control slick mauro said the 
surface oil in some samples was reduced to 30 percent of the 
original volume he said 
wynne and mauro conceded that weather and currents may have 
helped disperse the oil but were confident the microbes did their 
duty 
the best that anything else in our oil spill response arsenal 
can do is mitigate disaster mauro said 
the next step he said is persuading companies to include 
bioremediation in their oil spill contingency plans 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

