loggers cant harvest parts of 
privately owned forests where threatened spotted owls live under 
rules adopted by a state panel the decision could make california 
the first state to officially protect the species 
timber industry leaders immediately blasted wednesdays decision 
by the state board of forestry that could cut logging in northern 
california in half and could cost up to 1900 jobs 
im here representing the 25000 people who are going to be 
out of work because of your decision today said gil murray of 
the timber association of california 
environmentalists supported the decision because it protects old 
growth redwood trees where spotted owls have been found but they 
said a harvesting moratorium is needed 
weve got to become the first state to shut the door on this 
destruction to preserve jobs forests and a healthy planet said 
mark heitchue a santa cruz member of the environmental group earth 
first 
the regulations would take effect july 23 if they are approved 
by the states office of administrative law the rules would be in 
effect during the next three months until a more comprehensive 
protection plan is approved 
in june the us fish and wildlife service put the spotted owl 
on the threatened species list setting up the battle between the 
timber industry and environmentalists 
the regulations which apply to all counties north of marin 
dont ban logging entirely within areas where the owl lives but 
landowners wont be allowed to cut timber within 15 miles of where 
a spotted owl has been seen 
ross johnson chief of forest practice regulations for the 
california department of forestry and fire protection estimated 
timber yields will decrease from 35 percent to 50 percent under the 
temporary rules 
it could cost between 968 and 1901 jobs in lumber and related 
industries depending on how the rules are enforced he said 
biologists estimate that about 5000 pairs of spotted owls have 
survived recent years of clearcutting of old growth forests in 
washington oregon and california 
