<TEXT>
democrats and republicans took turns thursday 
decrying alleged tax dodging by us subsidiaries of foreign 
corporations but the treasury department would not concede there 
is wholesale cheating 
i propose were talking about billions in the range of 30 
billion a year in tax avoidance said rep jj pickle dtexas 
chairman of the house ways and means oversight subcommittee 
other members of the panel which has been investigating the 
problem for nine months put the figure at 50 billion 
we really do not have a way of estimating the tax loss said 
kenneth gideon assistant secretary of the treasury for tax policy 
i would find 50 billion very hard to accept because the us 
take from all corporations is only about twice that figure 
rep ronnie flippo dala asked if foreigncontrolled 
corporations were paying their share 
thats a question i cant answer gideon replied 
in many cases what we have is criminal conduct said rep 
clay shaw rfla the way these companies are operating i 
find incredible 
these companies are paying less than the average citizen the 
average taxpayers of the united states said rep richard 
schulze rpa thats abominable 
noting a movement to raise taxes to reduce the budget deficit 
schulze shouted ill be damned if ill do it while billions of 
dollars are floating overseas 
that sentiment was echoed by lawmakers as diverse as house 
majority leader richard gephardt dmo and sen jesse helms 
rnc 
the internal revenue service told the subcommittee earlier this 
week that foreign subsidiaries operating in the united states had 
revenues of 686 billion in 1987 and paid federal income tax of 
456 billion 
that rate of 066 percent of revenues compares with 104 percent 
paid that same year by usowned corporations 
subcommittee investigators examined 36 giant companies that 
distribute foreignmade automobiles motorcycles and consumer 
electronic goods in this country and found that more than half paid 
little or no tax over a 10year period 
the chief means of avoiding us tax was through a practice 
known as transfer pricing a foreign company could charge its us 
subsidiary an artificially high price for television sets for 
example thus lowering the amount of income subject to us tax 
such price manipulation also can worsen the us trade deficit 
and make it more difficult for american companies to compete 
abroad witnesses told the subcommittee 
michael e granfield vice chancellor of the university of 
california los angeles who assisted the irs in an earlier case 
against japanese automobile companies said there is a serious 
compliance problem 
granfield said the irs is hampered by a lack of resources and 
the inability to pay salaries high enough to retain personnel who 
can match expertise with industry economists and lawyers but the 
agency has other problems of its own creation including a penchant 
for seeking settlements that are so high as to be 
counterproductive he said 
it is transparent that the irs is not doing an adequate job in 
this area granfield said 
pickle expressed hope that the subcommittees investigation not 
be viewed as aimed solely as japanese corporations although 
government officials are barred by law from disclosing the names of 
taxpayers being investigated by the irs most of the criticism of 
subcommittee members has been aimed at japanese companies though 
not by name 
rep duncan hunter of california chairman of the house 
