<TEXT>
an advocacy group said in federal court 
thursday that the bush administration is dragging its feet on a 
judges order that surplus government property be made available 
for the homeless 
the group filed a motion seeking to enforce a 1988 permanent 
injunction requiring the federal government to correct violations 
and speed up implementation of the surplus property program 
the action was filed by the national law center on homelessness 
and poverty in us district court in washington 
the center said only 28 surplus federal properties have been 
made available to house the homeless despite a 1987 federal law and 
the 1988 court injunction issued by us district judge oliver 
gasch 
almost two years later the federal agencies are still doing 
everything possible to subvert this program said maria 
foscarinis director of the center a nonprofit advocacy group 
the federal government has barely lifted a finger to use its 
enormous existing resources to help those most in need 
the center contends in documents filed with the court that the 
department of housing and urban development has failed to 
adequately review federal properties that may be suitable for the 
homeless they also charged the application process is too 
burdensome and has discouraged nonprofit organizations from 
applying for surplus property to house homeless people 
the surplus property program was begun as part of a 1987 stewart 
b mckinney homeless assistance act which was named for its 
sponsor the late republican congressman from connecticut 
