<TEXT>
house and senate negotiators agreed late 
thursday that most singlehulled oil tankers should be phased out 
over the next 20 years and all new tankers should be built with 
double hulls 
the agreement removed a major obstacle to oil spill protection 
legislation congress has been debating since the devastating spill 
from the exxon valdez tanker off the alaska coast in march 1989 
members working out differences between the house and senate 
bills hope to complete action on the legislation before the 
upcoming august recess 
negotiators by voice vote agreed on a compromise timetable for 
removing socalled singlehulled tankers to phase out the oldest 
and largest ships beginning in 1995 a small number of tankers 
would be allowed to operate until 2015 but most would be gone by 
2010 
environmental groups in a letter to the conferees earlier this 
week called a requirement for doublehull tankers the single most 
important step congress can take to prevent oil spills the 
petroleum industry has opposed a requirement for double hulls 
there are more than 1300 tankers of various sizes that 
transport oil in and out of the united states and between us 
ports according to congressional estimates 
double hulls provide added protection if a tanker runs aground 
or collides with another ship there have been conflicting studies 
on whether the alaska spill would have been significantly reduced 
if the exxon valdez had a double hull 
the bill approved by the senate called for only a study of issue 
and the original house version would have phased out singlehull 
tankers by 2005 
environmental groups had called for the faster phaseout 
clifton curtis of friends of the earth called the compromise a 
kiss on the cheek followed by a slap in the face 
the tanker hull issue was one of the thorniest in a package that 
also calls for a 1 billion emergency response fund to deal with 
oil spill cleanup and sets liability levels for spills the 
emergency response fund will comes from a 50centabarrel levy on 
petroleum that began being collected last january 
senate and house sources said with the doublehull issue 
resolved the legislation the subject of intense negotiations 
between the house and senate for months may be approved before 
congress begins its summer recess aug 3 
under the compromise new tankers must be constructed with 
double hulls and existing singlehull tankers must begin to be 
phased out of operation in 1995 with the largest and oldest 
tankers to be taken out of service or retrofitted first 
sen ted stevens ralaska said that under the timetable 43 
percent of tankers would likely have double hulls by the end of the 
decade and 80 percent by the year 2005 tankers that unload oil 60 
miles outside us waters and tankers that already have double 
bottom or sides have until 2015 to comply 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

