<TEXT>
lockheed corp delivered the 59th and 
last f117a stealth fighter to the air force on thursday in a 
wellpublicized ceremony that contrasted sharply with the secrecy 
that veiled the jet for a decade 
delivery from lockheeds famed supersecret skunk works division 
comes as the defense firm girds for heated competition with 
northrop corp to build the advanced tactical fighter for the air 
force of the next century 
the atf contract for hundreds of warplanes is the last big 
ticket item on the pentagon shopping list for the end of the 20th 
century and represents the major spoils of what is left in the 
rapidly shrinking us defense budget 
gen michael j dugan the new air force chief of staff 
described the f117a as an example of a small is beautiful 
philosophy promoted by skunk works founder kelly johnson and noted 
that the program finished within budget and ahead of schedule 
we are going to be a smaller air force dugan said we are 
going to be a little smaller and little smarter small can be 
beautiful 
still at a cost of 426 million a plane the f117a remains 
one of the most expensive fighter aircraft ever built part of the 
cost resides in program secrecy imposed in 1981 
the project was accomplished with the strictest security 
measures known since the manhattan project to build the atom bomb 
during world war ii former defense secretary frank carlucci has 
said 
what the air force got for its money is a force of a little more 
than 50 planes the black sharply angled jet is actually a ground 
attack aircraft able to sneak past radar while dropping bombs with 
pinpoint accuracy 
the last delivery was announced in big newspaper advertisements 
which have become common in the aerospace industry since the 
defense budget began shrinking and firms and the services have 
become eager to show off advanced operational hardware that once 
was secret 
about 500 people attended the ceremony at lockheeds palmdale 
plant 
a northropled team has already rolled out its atf prototype but 
lockheeds prototype is not expected until late summer 
both northrop and lockheed are laying off many workers in 
southern california 
for lockheeds part the company hopes its breakthrough in 
stealth technology will help in the winnertakeall contract to 
build the atf 
the stealth fighter was built at the topsecret skunk works that 
developed such other hightechnology aircraft as the u2 and the 
mach 3 sr71 blackbird spyplanes 
let the nation know we are ready to do it again said skunk 
works chief ben rich 
if lockheed gets the atf contract the calabasas califbased 
contractor said it would build the fighters for the 63 billion 
program in georgia 
northrop would build atf planes in california at palmdale 
</TEXT>
