<TEXT>
the house passed landmark legislation on 
thursday guaranteeing rights to millions of disabled americans 
including access to public transportation businesses and jobs 
approval of the americans with disabilities act by a 37728 
vote came after house and senate negotiators agreed on a way to 
protect the jobs of aidsinfected workers who handle food 
rep william e dannemeyer rcalif and others tried 
unsuccessfully to restore an amendment that would have let 
employers keep aidsinfected workers away from foodhandling duties 
the senate will vote on the bill friday morning said senate 
majority leader george mitchell dmaine 
president bush has urged passage of the bill one of the most 
significant pieces of domestic legislation of his term the bill 
has been hailed as the most significant civil rights legislation 
since the 1964 act prohibiting racial discrimination 
it is indeed a bill which will open up america to 43 million 
americans who have been shut out sometimes consciously but too 
often subconsciously said the chief house sponsor rep steny 
hoyer dmd 
among the measures key provisions 
restaurants stores professional offices and all other 
businesses must make their services available to people with 
disabilities provided the cost of doing so is not excessive the 
requirement takes effect 18 months after enactment except for 
small businesses which would have longer 
businesses with 15 or more employees must disregard handicaps 
in hiring decisions and make special accommodations at the 
employers cost for those disabilities the accommodation is 
limited by the financial hardship it will cause for the company 
the requirement will be phased in over four years 
amtrak commuter rail systems and local and intercity bus 
systems will have to provide areas for disabled passengers 
including those in wheelchairs 
all telephone companies will have to provide special services 
for people with speech and hearing impairments 
opponents of the bill such as rep dan burton rind 
complain the bill is vaguely worded and will create a firestorm 
of lawsuits at the expense of the economy 
the bill caps two years of efforts including negotiations last 
summer with the white house 
the senate passed the bill last september by a 768 vote the 
house passed its version of the bill in may by a 40320 vote 
the house however added an amendment to let employers reassign 
workers with aids so they couldnt come into contact with food an 
attempt to resurrect that amendment failed thursday night by a 
224180 vote 
under a compromise approved earlier thursday by house and senate 
negotiators the department of health and human services would be 
required each year to study all communicable diseases and how they 
are transmitted the house vote on the bill approves that 
compromise which originated wednesday in the senate 
under the compromise employers in the food industry would be 
able to reassign workers whose diseases may be spread to customers 
through contact with food 
the compromise effectively negates the earlier house amendment 
health and human services secretary louis w sullivan and other 
leading health officials have repeatedly stated the disease cannot 
be spread through such casual contact 
proponents of the house amendment included sen jesse helms 
rnc who unsuccessfully sought to have the senate adopt it 
helms and others said public fears about aids could drive 
restaurants out of business despite scientific evidence 
those voting against the bill were 
reps bill archer rtexas richard k armey rtexas joe 
barton rtexas herbert h bateman rva dan burton rind jim 
chapman dtexas jim cooper dtenn philip m crane rill 
william e dannemeyer rcalif tom delay rtexas bill edwards 
rmo melton d hancock rmo j dennis hastert rill 
wally herger rcalif clyde c holloway rla jerry lewis 
rcalif jim lightfoot riowa ron marlenee rmont bob mcewen 
rohio clarence e miller rohio howard c nielson rutah jim 
olin dva ron packard rcalif mike parker dmiss norman d 
shumway rcalif bud shuster rpa charles w stenholm 
dtexas and bob stump rariz 
not voting were 
reps rod chandler rwash george w crockett jr dmich 
floyd h flake dny harold e ford dtenn william d ford 
dmich william f goodling dpa william h gray iii dpa 
frank j guarini dnj ralph m hall dtexas charles hatcher 
dga jerry huckaby dla ed jenkins dga ben jones dga 
donald e buz lukens rohio matthew g martinez dcalif 
