travel is hell 
an airport traffic jam delivers you to an endless line with 
luggage to lug to your narrow airplane seat for a meal of cute toy 
food a pressurized atmosphere and a bouncy landing worse to come 
back you reverse the procedure international travel can be 
unshirted hell exposing the unwary traveler to bad food bad 
service and bad company in a foreign language and an eccentric 
currency um how many shinplasters for that there fried zobrovny 
pardner 
great journeys an eightpart series bowing saturday night 
on pbs is another powerful incentive to stay home it reminds you 
just how miserable travel can be or how much fun if youre a 
masochist 
i love to travel you say 
and then you tell the whole story of your 13hour layover at 
krazed dictator international on the equator where sullen customs 
men teased sunburned sweaty germans in counterfeit chanel tshirts 
and you saw babies get sucked dry by malarial mosquitoes the size 
of dinner plates 
great journeys promises more of that kind of fun its first 
episode the silk road takes you through western china and some 
of the most desolate landscape ever seen outside a kitty box 
the publicity for great journeys says it will travel the 
worlds great trade routes with writers who make making personal 
journeys of passion along routes that hold personal significance 
for each of them hmm 
the opening episode takes colin thubron a wellregarded british 
novelist and travel writer along the silk traders caravan route 
from the great wall of china to well china he almost gets to 
afghanistan 
the lust for silk he explains nearly bankrupted the roman 
empire when travelers brought the fine fabric back from the orient 
the overland route flourished but has been in decline for oh 600 
years or so 
for thubron who chronicled a 10000mile road trip in his 1987 
book where nights are longest travels by car through western 
russia it must seem like a pleasant outing it exhausts even an 
armchair traveler 
along the way we see the waning influence of chinese culture 
it is gradually supplanted by the moslem people known as the 
turcomen farmers and traders whose culture is distinctly middle 
eastern and nonchinese 
theyre a handsome courteous people and they treat thubron with 
great restraint especially when he asks dumb questions q would 
you like to live in the city a certainly why not 
it turns out this journey has personal significance for thubron 
because he always wanted to do it judging from the landscape and 
his fellow travelers he is alone in that regard nobody but 
thubron is out there for recreation 
remember were talking trade route not scenic or 
fun route the terrain is flat and monotonous or hummocked and 
monotonous or mountainous and ugly a road runs through it he 
travels mostly by bus he loves it 
the silk traders skirted the great deserts not thubron he 
hires a couple of spitting toestomping camels and takes a daytrip 
onto the sand he loves it heck he even loves the camels who 
care for nothing but other camels 
he characterizes his journey as a solitary one this was 
probably a comfort to the invisible cameraman and sound operator 
who filmed his departing bus or arriving truck or his camel caravan 
endlessly rolling across the horizon 
mostly though thubron meditates on what it feels like to be in 
the last place god made 
other episodes of great journeys are much more promising 
than the silk road the burma road the salt road of the 
sahara the pan american highway and the ho chi minh trail will be 
featured in coming weeks 
and you dont have to leave home to see them 
