<TEXT>
if the usual measurements indicate stocks are 
priced rather high and the profit outlook is uninspiring and the 
economy seems to be going nowhere fast shouldnt the market 
averages fall 
if you think so you have lots of company among professional 
analysts some of whom have been saying for a year that the 
markets pricetoequity and pricetoearnings and 
pricetoprospects ratios are too high 
but the market never does what it should do the very word 
has no meaning whatsoever in regard to stock prices except to offer 
alibis to those who have been wrong or who wish to parade their 
academic knowledge 
that said why should the market ride higher on a weaker 
substructure than it has in the past or why shouldnt the popular 
bluechip averages revert to their proper behavior 
here are a few possibilities gleaned from analyst comments 
the institutionalization of the marketplace pension funds 
continue to grow their investment commitments are dictated not 
only by their analyses of stocks but by the need to put the money 
to use 
in a sense they must invest because of the large size of their 
transactions they must buy stocks in companies that also are large 
and have enough shares outstanding to accommodate largescale 
buying and selling 
when the market was made up of small traders there was more 
variability in their choices but individual investors continue to 
leave the market in the first quarter they reduced equity 
holdings at an annual rate of 91 billion 
the popular averages reflect prices of the biggest stocks and 
the activities of the biggest investors not all stocks are doing 
as well as the blue chips smaller stocks have been laggards for 
several years 
more big buyers are indexing their portfolios that is they 
seek to at least match the popular indexes most of which are 
bluechip indicators and they do so by buying the very stocks 
that make up the indexes 
the supply of equities is shrinking but the number of equity 
seekers may not be shrinking there are fewer stocks to buy today 
than there were last year or five years ago or seven years ago 
since 1983 according to wright investors service which 
closely monitors the equities population more than 500 billion of 
us equities have been removed from the stock market 
the shrinkage continued in the first quarter of 1990 according 
to wright which estimates that the value of equities retired 
exceeded the value of new issues by an annual rate of 63 billion 
in the 1980s most of the shrinkage resulted from corporate 
takeovers many of which substituted debt for equity more 
recently the decline seems to be resulting more from corporations 
buying back their own shares 
in late 1989 and early this year for example general electric 
ibm and westinghouse announced major stock repurchase programs that 
will total about 16 billion over the next several years 
what should the market be doing nothing but what it is 
doing 
