congressional candidate rosa delauro wants to 
use a big chunk of the peace dividend to help defense workers and 
industries adapt to the end of the cold war 
its a winwin proposal in her connecticut district which is 
dominated by three major military contractors already feeling the 
effects of friendlier relations around the world 
theres only one catch there might not be a peace dividend 
the cold war thaw is expected to produce military spending cuts 
adding up to tens of billions of dollars over the next few years 
but even as candidates tout their big plans for that money some 
politicians and analysts maintain the peace dividend is only a 
mirage 
the savings and loan bailout will eat it up rep dan 
rostenkowski of illinois told the nations mayors last month 
efforts to cut the federal deficit will swallow it others say 
any politician in an election year is going to grab for any 
available resource and spend it on the trail because they dont 
have anything else to spend said democratic analyst bob beckel 
but the pressure to take peace dividend money and use it for 
anything but deficit reduction is just too strong right now and 
this is coming from a liberal he added with a laugh 
the same argument is coming from republicans and fiscally 
conservative democrats like rostenkowski many of them contend that 
any peace dividend is too far down the road to mean much to voters 
anyway 
people cant relate to the argument said linda divall a 
gop polling consultant there is no 150 million surplus there on 
