<TEXT>
with the us newspaper empire he built on junk 
bonds and panache crumbling its not surprising that ralph m 
ingersoll ii has retreated to europe to pick up the pieces 
ingersoll whose network of newspaper holdings grew fast the 
past five years and shrank even faster earlier this month always 
considered himself an odd duck among american newspaper publishers 
hes been described as worldly softspoken debonair 
continental and global some acquaintances just call the 
44yearold entrepreneur a european kind of guy 
he speaks several languages went to school in switzerland 
wears english suits married a german drives a german car and when 
he dashes off a note he dates it the european way 2 july 1990 
that date july 2 was a turning point in the rise and fall of 
the media company started by ingersolls father ralph senior a 
respected editor who got into publishing in the late 1950s 
ingersoll announced a transatlantic swap with investment 
partner em warburg pincus amp co he gave up all his american 
newspapers and became sole owner of his european newspaper group 
ingersoll had controlled 10 american dailies and dozens of weeklies 
the swap also left ingersoll with a much smaller lessindebted 
business that includes a morning afternoon and sunday newspaper in 
dublin ireland and three dailies and 39 weeklies in england 
ingersoll said hes happy with the deal 
i think it was natural and basically inevitable ingersoll 
said in a telephone interview from the south of france where he was 
visiting friends we had a philosophical difference i saw great 
opportunity in europe they werent really interested 
he said the key to the deal for him is that hes severing his 
ties with warburg pincus his investment partner since 1983 
under his original agreement with that firm ingersoll was 
obligated to share 50 percent of the profits of any acquisition or 
deal he made after several years he realized he had made a 
mistake especially when he learned that warburg pincus wasnt 
particularly enthusiastic about european expansion 
i was faced with an opportunity to get out from under that 
agreement and i took advantage of it ingersoll said now im 
free to negotiate with individual investor groups for each 
individual deal thats the way my father and i did it for 25 years 
and thats the way im going to do it now 
nonetheless a basic question still emerges how much choice did 
he have in whats happened to him 
whats happening i think was basically forced upon him 
said john morton a media industry analyst for lynch jones amp ryan 
in new york but i guess with his affinity for europe it might 
make it easier to swallow 
others say ingersoll welcomes the chance to escape the recession 
that has hurt the american newspaper industry ingersoll said he 
talked with his partners about the transatlantic swap last year 
and has been watching the european market for eight years 
ralph always said there were greater opportunities in europe 
he always expressed a strong interest over there i think this move 
is consistent with his thinking said tom tallarico expublisher 
of ingersolls exnewspaper the st louis sun 
the sun launched last september was supposed to be a 
revolutionary tabloid designed to show that growth was possible in 
a stagnant industry 
after seven months the newspaper folded with a loss of at least 
25 million ingersoll who used some of his own money to start the 
paper said he stopped publishing because of inadequate street 
sales 
analysts said he was forced to pull the plug because of his 
weighty obligations in junk bonds the highyield highrisk debt 
securities that became a primary financing tool for many companies 
in the 1980s 
by some reckonings ingersolls us newspaper network amassed 
debts exceeding 700 million much of it raised by michael milken 
the junkbond financier of the nowdefunct drexel burnham lambert 
inc investment company 
a month before the suns demise ingersoll offered to repurchase 
240 million worth of junk bonds at deep discounts to avoid 
defaulting on upcoming interest payments he got a poor response 
everyone in the industry said the st louis sun was illfated 
from the start said kenneth berents a stock analyst with alex 
brown amp co in baltimore and its interesting that had he not 
gone out on a limb for the sun he might not be having the problems 
hes having today the sun may have cost him his whole empire 
ingersoll said the junk bond troubles had nothing to do with his 
decision to make the transatlantic swap and hes not sure where 
the startup of the sun fits into the picture 
it didnt figure in it directly but i suppose it may have had 
some type of metaphysical impact on what warburg pincus was 
thinking but its hard to say ingersoll said 
its difficult to say much about the internal finances of 
ingersolls companies because they are privately owned even 
bondholders have a hard time obtaining information about them 
but its clear that things havent been easy for ingersoll since 
the sun stopped publishing april 25 
i think the failure of the sun affected him more than anyone 
thought it disenchanted him with american newspapers said kevin 
horrigan the suns lead columnist who was lured away from the st 
louis postdispatch ralph felt he had something to contribute 
and was basically told no thanks 
so horrigan said hes not surprised to see ingersoll going to 
europe actually many acquaintances say theyre not surprised to 
see ingersoll going to europe because hes more attuned to that 
culture 
when newspaper analysts and other experts said that starting a 
new metropolitan newspaper couldnt de done ingersoll rattled off 
the names of several recent successful startups in europe and 
elsewhere 
at one point while his sun was struggling with sagging 
circulation and an identity problem in st louis ingersoll was in 
england having dinner with prince charles 
ingersoll hinted he hasnt given up on us newspapers 
completely the financial problems in the industry probably will 
create opportunities for newspaper entrepreneurs with a global view 
to pick up some bargains he said 
maybe in a perfect world one would operate on every 
continent ingersoll said 
for now ingersolls world is less than perfect 
