<TEXT>
the dangerous legacy of 45 years of building 
atomic bombs is contaminated nuclear graveyards that will cost 
billions of dollars to clean up if indeed scientists can figure 
out a way to clean them up one researcher even says that trying to 
get rid of the radioactive wastes would cost more lives than 
leaving them alone 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
miles of 8foothigh electric fences 
stretch through bethel valley the oncesecret cradle of the atomic 
age they stand watch over burial grounds of deadly wastes that are 
the legacy of four decades of nuclear bomb production 
yellow and magenta signs proclaim radiation hazard keep 
out 
the fences encircling some of the hundreds of acres of 
contaminated land on the federal oak ridge nuclear weapons compound 
are reminders that while the cold war may be over it took a 
serious toll 
it cost about 250 billion for the roughly 65000 nuclear 
weapons that the united states has manufactured since 1945 when 
the first was assembled that bill is paid yet to be settled is 
the toll this secretive manufacturing process has taken on weapons 
workers and the environment 
at oak ridge alone the energy department has spent 1 billion 
since 1983 trying to control the environmental damage it is 
expected to take at least 10 more years just to determine what 
poisons have seeped into the soil and ground water here and 20 
more years to stop it from spreading 
the total bill for cleaning up oak ridge may top 12 billion 
costs at some of the 16 other active nuclear arms laboratories 
manufacturing plants and proving grounds in 11 other states will be 
much higher 
the full cost of environmental repairs alone may top 100 
billion estimates vary greatly because the government itself 
doesnt know how badly some sites are contaminated nor has all the 
necessary technology been developed 
the energy department which makes and tests all nuclear weapons 
for the pentagon said in a report on july 3 that the magnitude of 
the cleanup is expanding so rapidly that it cannot keep up its 
cost estimate for the next five years is 314 billion nearly 50 
percent more than it expected just one year ago and this is in the 
early days the full cleanup effort will take at least 30 years 
these amounts challenge and almost certainly exceed the 
cleanup resources available to the government and its hundreds of 
private contractors the report said 
in the meantime tennessee health authorities ban fishing and 
swimming in east fork poplar creek which winds through the 
56000acre weapons plant as well as the adjacent city of oak 
ridge and in a portion of the clinch river which borders the 
plant on three sides the stream is poisoned by mercury once used 
to separate lithium for nuclear weapons 
oak ridge originally called the clinton engineer works was the 
site of the first nuclear bomb production plants codenamed y12 
x10 and k25 today it remains a key link in the production chain 
although some of its operations have been closed permanently 
martin marietta energy systems inc which runs oak ridge under 
a government contract says 75 tons of toxic mercury and 
substantial amounts of the radioactive element cesium137 have 
spread from the weapons plant and contaminated the sediment in 
watts bar reservoir which remains open to the public for swimming 
and boating 
not only did the atomic age start here the problems did 
too says bill adams the energy departments chief of waste and 
environmental management at oak ridge 
unfortunately the problems dont end here 
the radioactive and toxic contamination is so bad at several 
nuclear weapons plants in colorado ohio tennessee south 
carolina california missouri and washington state that portions 
of these huge sites will become national sacrifice zones 
scientists say land deemed permanently unfit for human use 
we have one hell of a legacy to clean up says leo duffy 
the top adviser to energy secretary james d watkins on longterm 
environmental issues 
the legacy is not just environmental insults its damage to 
human health damage long suspected by workers and plant neighbors 
but routinely denied by the government until watkins two years ago 
began tearing down the walls of secrecy 
on july 11 more than 40 years after the fact the energy 
department acknowledged the hanford plutonium production plant in 
southcentral washington state leaked radiation at levels that 
endangered the health of nearby residents 
it was the governments first admission that the hanford leaks 
were at levels sufficient to cause cancer and other illnesses in 
people living near the facility 
the energy department is committed to cleaning up the 
environmental damage even if it has made few promises about 
addressing the problem of health risks the question is how to get 
the money needed to restore the soil and water 
congress and the bush administration are under pressure to cut 
the budget deficit even as defense spending slows in response to 
moves toward democracy in eastern europe and the soviet union 
in the emerging national debate over the size of a peace 
dividend from expected military savings and how to spend it 
little has been said about the mortgage the atomic bomb 
builders took out to compete in the arms race 
during the world war ii development of the first atomic bombs in 
the armys secret manhattan project any thoughts of environmental 
or excessive health risks were subsumed by a feeling that the very 
survival of democracy depended on getting the bomb as quickly as 
possible 
later through the cold war period military authorities used 
the shield of strict secrecy justified on national security 
grounds to continue borrowing against the environment and 
workers health to speed up bomb production according to 
interviews with current and former arms plant workers government 
officials scientists and congressional investigators 
now payment is coming due 
officials who have surveyed the dozens of existing and former 
nuclear weapons sites around the country say hundreds of billions 
of dollars are needed not only to control environmental damage but 
also to reduce the health risks of nuclear plant workers and to 
make safety improvements long put off 
until the mid1980s the government would not acknowledge these 
failures 
nobody wants to look under the rug and a lot has been swept 
under the rug in the nuclear weapons industry says elizabeth 
paul of the snake river alliance based in ketchum idaho the 
citizens group opposes the idaho national engineering laboratory 
which recovers highly enriched uranium from naval reactors 
even an investment of 100 billion in environmental corrections 
wont completely reverse the damage 
the chief problems are contamination of the soil and ground 
water on the federal sites and in surrounding areas with 
radioactive materials such as plutonium tritium and strontium90 
and such toxics as mercury arsenic and a variety of solvents 
</TEXT>
