<DOCNO> AP900712-0199 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
congress needs to overhaul regulation of the 
securities and banking industries according to the head of the 
securities and exchange commission but he isnt ready to recommend 
the best way to do it 
in testimony before a house panel wednesday sec chairman 
richard c breeden also outlined several suggestions for reversing 
us financial firms declining market share over the last decade 
but he cautioned against piecemeal change for the mere sake of 
change 
the level of unnecessary costs created by the us regulatory 
system could become a significant factor in the international 
competitiveness of us firms breeden told a subcommittee 
considering proposals to update a nearly 60yearold banking law 
he noted that in 1970 seven of the worlds 25 largest banks were 
based in the united states while today just one is usbased with 
most of the others are headquartered in japan 
breeden was among several witnesses testifying before the 
finance subcommittee of the house energy and commerce committee 
critics of existing regulation have called for repealing the 
glasssteagall act the depressionera law that keeps most banks 
out of the securities business and vice versa 
such regulations critics maintain make the united states less 
able to compete for investment in the evershrinking global 
marketplace 
but breeden warned that deregulation must be a twoway street 
he said if congress repeals glasssteagall it simultaneously should 
amend the bank holding company act of 1956 to permit bank ownership 
by nonbanking companies 
banks should not be free to acquire securities firms while 
many securities and other major us firms remain as a practical 
matter unable to acquire banks he said 
similar views were expressed by other witnesses including 
samuel j baptista president of the financial services council a 
washingtonbased trade group of 25 banks securities firms and 
other financial service companies 
the issue at hand is not deregulation not reregulation and 
not broader powers for banks he said the issue before 
congress is comprehensive restructuring of our financial services 
industry that will benefit both financial services providers and 
consumers 
among his recommendations were opening all financial businesses 
to all companies financial and commercial that meet safety and 
soundness tests baptista also called for functional regulation 
whereby the banking operations of a financial firm would be 
regulated by banking regulators and the securities part by 
securities regulators 
richard stuart former head of the bank capital markets 
association a trade association of 100 banks and david silver 
president of the investment company institute a trade group 
representing mutual funds also supported functional regulation 
banks securities firms and others should be allowed to offer 
all financial services silver said 
in addition to repealing the 1933 glasssteagall act silver 
called for amending the bank holding company act so that it no 
longer confines the banking business to a restricted group of 
players 
in his testimony breeden critiqued ways of regulating financial 
firms after the barriers come down 
one version universal banking which allows banks to engage 
directly in a broad range of financial activities was fatally 
flawed he said 
universal banking which is used in west germany and elsewhere 
in europe would expand federal deposit insurance guarantees to 
bank ventures in the securities and insurance industries that 
would increase taxpayer risk in the event of a banks losses he 
said 
also no single federal regulator has the capability or expertise 
to examine all the different types of financial products that could 
be offered under universal banking breeden said 
</TEXT>
