<TEXT>
the bush administrations move to transfer 
authority for stockindex futures from one regulatory agency to 
another now faces testimony from supporters of the securities and 
exchange commission 
the administration is pushing legislation that would strip the 
commodity futures trading commission of regulatory authority over 
stockindex futures and hand it to the rival sec 
the senate banking housing and urban affairs committee is to 
conclude two days of hearings today with backers of the sec 
on wednesday sen christopher bond rmiss suggested a 
compromise that would allow the cftc to retain most regulation but 
allow the federal reserve board to set margin levels for trading 
stockindex futures 
margins are the downpayments or collateral paid by investors who 
buy securities or futures contracts on credit 
bond said the administration does not have enough senate votes 
to pass its measure 
stockindex futures often used in program trading strategies by 
large institutional investors such as pension funds allow 
investors to trade on the movement of a basket of stocks without 
having to buy the underlying stocks 
the cftc and the futures industry oppose any shift saying it 
will cripple the agencys ability to regulate other futures 
products and overregulate a segment of an industry thats battling 
to stave off foreign competition 
but the sec and the treasury department argue the move is 
necessary to curb volatility in the stock markets arising out of 
price differences between the futures and securities markets 
treasury secretary nicholas brady is scheduled to appear before 
the committee later today and witnesses representing the futures 
industry were slated to testify later this month 
the administration bill also seeks to give the sec authority to 
set margins for stockindex futures currently futures margins are 
set by the exchanges usually only a fraction of the amount 
required in securities transactions 
on wednesday a former top official of the chicago mercantile 
exchange blasted the cftc as a pygmy of federal regulation 
it was the second time thomas f eagleton who resigned from the 
merc last year had harsh words for the commodity futures trading 
commission 
last year his criticism came in a hearing before the senate 
agriculture committee which oversees the cftc 
in his testimony eagleton a former democratic senator from 
missouri criticized the cftcs light regulatory touch and its 
limited resources to investigate illegal activities 
the cftc is about as sluggish a regulatory agency as one can 
find he told the committee members 
recalling last years fbi undercover investigation of fraud in 
the chicago futures pits that led to more than 40 indictments 
eagleton said 
after the sting the cftc this pygmy of federal regulation 
overwhelmed by its daytoday operations came plodding along with 
toolittle toolate to catch fastmoving crooks and fastchanging 
events 
also testifying before the banking committee in favor of the 
jurisdictional switch were representatives of the national 
association of securities dealers the american stock exchange and 
the options clearing corp 
