<TEXT>
canadian forest products giant abitibiprice 
inc and two british publishers have agreed to buy a venture that 
has been exploring building a newsprint plant in scotland that 
would use only recycled fiber 
abitibiprice said thursday the partners would build the plant 
in gartcosh scotland under certain conditions that include 
updating engineering studies and cost estimates and securing 
approval from their respective boards 
terms of the deal were not disclosed it comes amid growing 
global demand that newpaper companies increase their use of 
recycled newsprint to help preserve natural resources 
abitibiprices partners are londonbased publishing companies 
the daily telegraph plc led by conrad black and mirror group 
newspapers ltd led by robert maxwell 
the publishing companies each would own 25 percent of the 
venture called north british newsprint ltd while abitibiprice of 
toronto would own 50 percent and operate the newsprint mill 
according to an announcement by the companies 
it said groundbreaking for the plant could take place in the 
first half of 1991 and construction time would take about two years 
bernd koken chairman and chief executive of abitibiprice said 
the mill would give his company a newsprint manufacturing presence 
in the european community the company now has nine newsprint 
plants all in north america 
the north british newsprint project was conceived and developed 
by stirling fibre a leading british waste paper merchant that has 
been working on it for several years 
we are delighted that abitibiprice and its partners are 
taking over this outstanding project chairman christopher 
wilkins of stirling said in a statement 
current estimates are that the plant will cost about 200 million 
pounds or about 360 million at recent exchange rates it is to 
produce 220000 metric tons per year of newsprint using about 
270000 metric tons of old newspapers and magazines 
the newsprint is expected to be sold mainly in the united 
kingdom 
</TEXT>
