<DOCNO> AP900712-0237 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
six months after the federatedallied 
department store empire plunged into the biggest retailing 
bankruptcy case in history it still hasnt produced a plan to 
repay 77 billion in debts reorganize and survive 
but suppliers and creditors dont seem overly concerned and 
some are optimistic about the future of the stores which span some 
of the bestknown names in retailing including bloomingdales 
jordan marsh and the bon marche 
federated department stores inc and allied stores corp the 
retailing divisions of the campeau corp in toronto are still 
bleeding substantial amounts of money 
both lost nearly 100 million in the first full quarter under 
federal bankruptcy protection last week they reported a combined 
loss of 269 million in may alone 
nonetheless they said the may loss was smaller than expected 
and four of their nine chains recorded operating profits for the 
month seattlebased the bon marche reported the largest profit 
39 million 
from every indication we see they are on the right track and 
we are going to support them in every way we can said bernard 
chaus president of clothing supplier bernard chaus inc 
chaus said he plans to ship the stores merchandise worth 30 
million to 40 million this year thats an indication of faith 
among many suppliers that the department stores will emerge 
successfully from their financial problems 
a federal bankruptcy court has twice granted federated and 
allied extensions on their deadline to submit a plan to reorganize 
giving them until sept 12 after that date creditors can propose 
their own plans 
the retailers say they plan to ask judge j vincent aug for at 
least one more extension at a hearing later this month 
federated and allied sought protection from creditors jan 15 
under chapter 11 of the federal bankruptcy code the biggestever 
bankruptcy case in the retail industry the move gives them a 
respite while they devise a plan to pay the bills and emerge as 
healthy businesses 
the retailers had been struggling to repay enormous debts that 
accrued from campeaus takeover of allied in 1986 and of federated 
in 1988 much of the debt was in risky highyield junk bonds 
that developer robert campeau sold to finance his companys 
expansion in the united states 
the stores themselves have remained largely healthy despite 
pockets of weakness in the retailing industry for that reason 
some creditors have asked why the stores should remain in 
bankruptcy court refuge at all since it is the parent company that 
was mostly responsible for the crippling debts 
the court protection has delayed major decisions on expansion 
plans and financing arrangements lewis s rosenbloom a lawyer for 
the retailers major suppliers said such protection could be 
costly for the stores 
the next major step in the case will be for federated and allied 
to propose a plan to run the businesses in reorganization 
spokeswoman carol sanger said the plan is due by late summer or 
early autumn 
i think until we see the companies business plan later this 
summer it is difficult even to begin negotiating over 
reorganization said lawyer joseph f kelly who represents 
holders of 12 billion in federated and allied junk bonds 
while creditors await a reorganization plan the decision to 
appoint federated veteran allen i questrom chairman and chief 
executive officer has reassured some suppliers 
questrom considered one of the nations best retailers was 
hired away from dallasbased neimanmarcus in february he had 
spent 23 years in federated divisions before resigning in 1988 
questrom is implementing new marketing strategies and cutting 
out unprofitable segments of private label clothing brands said 
thomas tashjian a retail industry analyst for seidler amdec 
securities inc 
as long as the losses remain reasonable within a wide range of 
expectations i dont think the figures are really an issue i 
really think the reassessment of strategy is more important 
tashjian said and i expect them to emerge from chapter 11 as a 
very strong vibrant competitor in the department store business 
