<TEXT>
marcelo gumucio president and chief 
operating officer of cray research inc on thursday resigned from 
both positions at the supercomputer maker 
cray chairman and chief executive officer john a rollwagen said 
for the foreseeable future he will assume gumucios 
responsibilities in addition to retaining his titles of chairman 
and chief executive officer 
rollwagen said in a letter to employees that he and gumucio 
were unable to agree on implementing a longrange strategy for 
the company 
we attempted to blend our distinct management styles 
effectively but were not successful in that effort rollwagen 
said the decision to part is mutual and in the best overall 
interests of the organization and the individuals involved 
gumucio who also resigned from the cray board of directors did 
not return a phone call thursday he joined the company in 1983 as 
executive vice president of marketing becoming president in 1988 
it boils down to a style difference maybe not even a 
personality difference rollwagen said in an interview after the 
announcement 
my style is somewhat more intuitive and informal whereas 
marcelo is more structured and more formal thats one way to try 
to put a handle on it neither style is right nor wrong both 
styles have worked very effectively in a lot of companies 
including ours 
the problem is from trying to marry two styles at top of the 
company rollwagen said 
rollwagen emphasized there was no disagreement with gumucio over 
longrange strategies the company has been developing absolutely 
not we have full agreement on strategy he said 
at the companys annual meeting in may gumucio said cray 
planned to continue expanding its line of supercomputers in the 
1990s he said the companys introduction of a new smaller 
supercomputer was an example of how the company was developing 
outward from its original focus on the most powerful computers 
cray now is refocused on a variety of products to fit the 
growing world of computer networking he said then 
cray suffered a slump in 1989 with sales up just 4 percent to 
7847 million and earnings declining 43 percent to 89 million 
in april however cray reported its firstquarter profit 
totaled 95 million compared with 15 million for the same 
period in 1989 the company also said it expected an increase in 
profit for the year 
analyst gary smaby president of the minneapolisbased smaby 
group said he met with rollwagen and gumucio after the 
announcement thursday 
my sense is the differences were stylistic differences he 
said there was no particular event or issue that caused them to 
reach this decision it built up over a period of years 
the change should be a positive one for cray smaby said 
any time conflicts are resolved it bodes well for the health 
of the enterprise it helps people focus on the work at hand he 
said 
smaby said gumucio told him he had not yet decided on his future 
plans and did not have another job lined up 
</TEXT>
