<TEXT>
southmark corps former top officers caused the 
collapse of the real estate concern and then concealed its failing 
financial condition with the help of outside auditors a 
courtappointed examiner charged 
examiner neal batson said in a report filed last friday that 
dallasbased southmark which is operating under chapter 11 of the 
federal bankruptcy code should pursue claims against former 
chairman gene phillips and former vice chairman william friedman to 
recover a portion of an estimated 15 billion in losses the 
company allegedly suffered during their eightyear tenure 
batson also urged southmark to investigate a severance agreement 
reached last year between the company and former officers 
at the recommendation of the examiner southmarks creditors 
committee last month filed suit against phillips and friedman 
seeking to recover roughly 68 million in payments and rights 
surrendered to the officers 
the report also advised the company to take legal action against 
grant thornton southmarks outside auditor from the early 1980s 
until 1988 batson wrote that grants improper accounting was 
key to maintaining the illusion that southmark was a growing and 
profitable company even as it slid toward insolvency 
in a statement grant thornton denied any wrongdoing 
concluding that southmark was insolvent by december 1987 the 
examiner tried in the report to explain how the 9 billion company 
saw its net worth wiped out with one quarters losses and wound up 
in bankruptcy court struggling to repay 1 billion in junk bonds 
with stock of doubtful value and 644 million in cash 
the story of southmarks rise and fall involved its ability to 
create the illusion of success and prosperity that deceived the 
investing public with a selfportrait of everincreasing profits 
assets and net worth batson wrote in the report the last to 
arise from his investigation into the prebankruptcy affairs of the 
company 
the southmark story is one of unsound acquisitions overvalued 
assets illusory sales phantom profits hidden liabilities 
insider deals and outsider cronyism resulting in a sea of red 
ink he said 
attorneys for phillips and friedman who said they hadnt yet 
seen the independent examiners latest report criticized its 
general findings 
henry simon one of the mens bankruptcy lawyers said all 
highly leveraged real estate companies in texas suffered the same 
fate as southmark and that the states real estate crash not 
mismanagement was responsible for southmarks woes 
so far theres no one who has received a business achievement 
award for doing highly leveraged deals simon said 
grant thornton said in a statement it emphatically disagrees 
with the report charging the findings are supported neither by 
generally accepted accounting principles nor generally accepted 
auditing standards 
the accounting firm defended its work calling its audits 
extremely vigorous it said its audit resulted in a 200 
million loss for fiscal 1988 in place of the 6 million profit 
southmarks story is that of a failed business not an audit 
failure it said southmark did not fail because of its 
auditor grant will not allow itself to be made a scapegoat and 
will defend itself vigorously 
under the bankruptcy reorganization plan outlined wednesday at 
the first day of the hearing southmark would contribute 100 
million in new assets to its san jacinto savings unit the 
centerpiece of the proposed reorganization and repay creditors 
holding more than 1 billion in claims with cash new debt and 
stock in the reorganized company 
