<TEXT>
fisherprice toys announced thursday it 
was cutting 720 jobs as it struggles amid weak sales mounting 
losses and an expected spinoff from its parent company 
the maker of brightly colored preschool toys said it was laying 
off 245 employees at its upstate new york headquarters and closing 
a nearby plant later this year 
fisherprice in february closed its plant in east aurora where 
the company was founded 60 years ago 
fisherprice which employs 6500 employees in plants in new 
york kentucky england and on the usmexico border has lost 
445 million in the last 15 months company president ronald j 
jackson said fisherprice sales dipped to 700 million in fiscal 
1990 from 849 million the previous year 
he said the latest layoffs werent necessarily related to the 
scheduled spinoff in early 1991 of fisherprice from its current 
owner quaker oats co of chicago 
whether youre a part of quaker oats or a public company you 
just cant go forward losing money he said i think these cuts 
would be made whether it was part of quaker or whether it was 
independent 
fisherprice said it was closing its plant in holland which was 
built in 1962 and employs about 475 workers between september and 
november because it is the companys oldest facility 
the cutbacks at its headquarters where the company will retain 
a work force of about 950 employees involve all phases of the 
operation including marketing research and development 
operations and engineering 
david leibowitz a toy industry analyst with american securities 
corp said the layoffs are designed to get fisherprice into 
fighting trim before the spinoff from quaker oats 
these are very hard things to do but the reality is if this 
company goes independent early next year and does not have a strong 
parent to fall back on during hard times they have to be able to 
stand on their own two feet he said 
jackson who just joined the company seven weeks ago said 
company executives had been enthusiastic about the reception 
fisherprices products received at the annual toy fair the 
company had promised no further layoffs in upstate new york 
by the time they got to april and saw the business trends 
our products just werent doing as well as wed hoped he said 
he said most of fisherprices losses can be attributed to the 
companys decision within the past 10 years to branch out from its 
traditionally strong infant and preschool product lines 
the promotion line of toys was aimed at and marketed to children 
between the ages of 5 and 12 had only initial success and the 
company has withdrawn from that line jackson said 
he said fisherprice would refocus on infant and preschool 
products 
</TEXT>
