<DOCNO> AP900712-0256 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
the securities and exchange commission on 
thursday charged the troubled colorado penny stock brokerage 
blinder robinson amp co of overcharging investors by more than 20 
million in 21 months 
according to a lawsuit filed in us district court blinder 
robinson marked up prices as high as 140 percent on penny stocks 
when selling them to investors 
sec attorney stephen j crimmins said companies are permitted to 
mark up prices as much as 10 percent as commission for conducting 
transactions but they must notify buyers if they charge more than 
that he said blinder did not 
the sec complaint said the alleged illegal activity took place 
from june 1985 through february 1987 with some occurring in 
pennsylvania 
in april the sec suspended blinder robinson from trading in 
penny stocks for 45 days and from underwriting such offerings for 
two years the sec also barred the firms founder and chairman 
meyer blinder from associating with and registered brokerdealer 
for at least two years 
blinder 69 of denver colo and four associates were indicted 
in february on racketeering and securities fraud charges by a 
federal grand jury in las vegas the indictment followed a 1988 
internal revenue service raid on blinder robinsons denver office 
blinder robinson once was the nations largest penny stock 
brokerage 
penny stocks are low cost high risk securities usually trading 
for less than 3 per share they are not listed on stock exchanges 
and typically are used to raise capital for new or small companies 
the lack or reliable information about penny stocks has made them 
prone to fraud 
the complaint charged that of more than 1 billion shares of 
penny stocks in 12 companies blinder robinson sold to customers 
997 percent were marked up by over 10 percent of the prevailing 
market price 
blinder robinson general counsel kalmon glovin said the lawsuit 
appeared to be a rehashing of old allegations by the sec which 
blinder robinson and meyer blinder have been and are being 
vigorously defended against in other litigation 
glovin said the sec was relentless in trying to justify 
systematic destruction of blinder robinson and the 
professional career of its founder meyer blinder under the guise 
of protecting the public interest 
the philadelphia lawsuit also charges that blinder robinson bid 
for and purchased stocks at the same time it was distributing them 
to customers crimmins said the practice is considered legal if a 
firm informs buyers but blinder robinson did not 
the sec also charges that the firm dominated the market in the 
12 stocks accounting for over 86 percent of all interdealer and 
retail trading activity a practice which resulted in essentially 
giving the company complete control of the price of the stocks 
the sec seeks permanent injunctions against the alleged illegal 
practices crimmins declined to say whether other federal agencies 
would pursue criminal charges against the company or its officers 
intercontinental enterprises inc the englewood colo 
corporation that owns blinder robinson also is named in the suit 
along with blinder robinson and meyer blinder 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

