<TEXT>
federal express corp said thursday that 
profits rose 53 percent in its fourth quarter but slumped for the 
full year in large part because of the acquisition of tiger 
international 
earnings for the quarter were 431 million or 81 cents a 
share up from 4097 million or 78 cents a share in the same 
1989 period revenue rose 147 percent to 19 billion from 17 
billion 
for the fiscal year ending may 31 profits fell 305 percent to 
116 million or 218 a share from 185 million or 318 a share 
in fiscal 1989 revenue rose to 7 billion from 52 billion 
federal express spokesman dan copp said the annual decline in 
earnings was due largely to increased debt resulting from the 
acquisition in february of tiger international a los angelesbased 
air cargo carrier 
copp said the companys net interest expense more than doubled 
in fiscal 1989 to 188 million due to the purchase of tiger 
international and was the primary reason for the earnings decline 
federal express longterm debt increased to more than 2 
billion from about 75 million a year because of the acquisition of 
tiger international 
federal express chief executive frederick w smith also cited 
international expansion disappointing air freight volumes and 
expansions at major hub facilities in anchorage and indianapolis 
also contributed to the earnings result 
federal express is the worlds largest air delivery service 
